## What happened

Apple's **Security.framework** has never natively supported DSA. In earlier .NET versions on macOS, the runtime shimmed DSA via a bundled/brew-linked **OpenSSL**. Microsoft has been deprecating DSA since .NET 7 (`SYSLIB0024`), and in **.NET 11 the OpenSSL-backed fallback on macOS was removed**, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

Windows and Linux still work because they have OS-level DSA support (CNG and OpenSSL respectively).

## How to fix it

**Option A — Use `DSAOpenSsl` explicitly (short-term, verify-only):**

```csharp
using System.Security.Cryptography;

// Instead of DSA.Create(), explicitly use the OpenSSL implementation.
// Requires OpenSSL installed on the macOS host (e.g. `brew install openssl`).
using var dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyParams);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

> `DSAOpenSsl` lives in `System.Security.Cryptography.OpenSsl` and directly P/Invokes OpenSSL, bypassing the platform gate in `DSA.Create()`.

**Option B — Use BouncyCastle (no native dependency):**

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;

var signer = new DsaDigestSigner(new DsaSigner(), new Sha1Digest());
signer.Init(forSigning: false, new DsaPublicKeyParameters(y, new DsaParameters(p, q, g)));
signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
```

This is fully managed — no OS crypto dependency at all.

**Option C — Migrate away from DSA (long-term, recommended):**

DSA is cryptographically weak by modern standards. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (`RSA` also works). This eliminates the deprecation problem entirely.

### TL;DR

| Approach | Effort | Cross-platform | Future-proof |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DSAOpenSsl` | Low | Needs OpenSSL on mac | No (still deprecated) |
| BouncyCastle | Medium | Yes | Yes |
| Migrate to ECDSA | High | Yes | Yes |

For a verify-only legacy scenario, **BouncyCastle** is the pragmatic middle ground — no native deps and no deprecation risk.
